\section{Bootstrapping bytecodes (simplified)}
\label{sec:simplified-bootstrap}

%claude:
As I mentioned earlier, [[rc]] does not start by compiling source code;
it starts by {\em interpreting} a small series of hand-crafted bytecodes
called the {\em bootstrap}.
%
In its simplest form, the bootstrap just contains [<Xrdcmds>],
the bytecode that reads a command, compiles it, and starts
a new thread to execute it.
%
The first element is the reference count (set to 1), and
the last element is a zero {sentinel} marking the end of the code vector.
%
The actual bootstrap is more complex (see Chapter~\ref{chap:initialization-real}):
it sources the [[rcmain]] initialization script, which sets up
the default [[$path]] and runs the user's profile, but for now
it is simpler to assume the simpler bootstrap below.

<<[[main()]] locals>>=
int i;
@

%OPTIONAL
<<[[main()]] initialize [[boostrap]] (simplified)>>=
memset(bootstrap, 0, sizeof bootstrap);

i = 0;
bootstrap[i++].i = 1; // reference count
bootstrap[i++].f = Xrdcmds;
bootstrap[i].i = 0;
@
%alt:
% bootstrap[i++].f = XMark; ? necessary?
%said-later: bootstrap[i++].f = Xexit; ? Xexit never reached I think.
% 1 to reference count? why? they put 0 in compile() for new bytecodes
%ocaml: no need end of list, no need reference count

\section{Setting [[runq]]}

%claude:
[<start()>] creates a new thread and pushes it on top of [<runq>].
The program counter starts at 1 (not 0) because element 0 of
any code vector is reserved for the reference count.
%
Note how [<start()>] links the new thread to the old [<runq>]
through [[p->ret = runq]]: this is how the interpreter
knows where to resume after the current thread finishes.

<<[[main()]] initialize [[runq]] with bootstrap code>>=
start(bootstrap, 1, (var *)nil);
@

<<function [[start]]>>=
/// main | Xrdcmds -> <>
void
start(code *c, int pc, var *local)
{
    struct Thread *p = new(struct Thread);

    p->code = codecopy(c);
    p->pc = pc;

    p->argv = nil;
    p->local = local;

    p->cmdfile = nil;
    p->cmdfd = nil;
    p->lineno = 1;
    p->eof = false;
    p->iflag = false;

    <<[[start()]] set redir>>

    // add_stack(runq, p)
    p->ret = runq;
    runq = p;
}
@
%alt: should call it new_thread() because it does not
%  start it right away, and should do the add_stack in the caller.
%ocaml: I renamed it mk_thread and do runq := t::!run in the caller. clearer.

% not reset iflast to false?

% called sometimes with pc different of 1? yes, for async, trap,  pipe, etc.

% will go back to previous Thread (put in runq stack) if
% the new code does some Xreturn.
% So idea of subcomputation. With then fresh argv, fresh code list.

% When call start()? main, Xrdcmds. Xrdcmds is really a read/eval/print loop.

% very first time runq should be nil so p->ret points to nil.

\section{Setting [[runq->argv]]}

%claude:
Now that [<runq>] is set, [<main()>] populates its argument stack
with the command-line arguments. These arguments are pushed
in reverse order because [<pushword()>] prepends to the list,
so the first argument ends up at the top.
%
The actual bootstrap code will later assign this list to [[$*]]
(the script arguments variable).

<<global [[argv0]]>>=
/*
 * Start executing the given code at the given pc with the given redirection
 */
char *argv0="rc";
@
% used by? it is overriden below, but used by what after?

<<[[main()]] initialize [[runq->argv]]>>=
/* prime bootstrap argv */
pushlist();
argv0 = strdup(argv[0]);
for(i = argc-1; i!=0; --i) 
    pushword(argv[i]);
@

% does getflags consume argv and argc? Yes! so push only non flags
%ocaml: no need to call pushlist() here. Already have working argv.
% no nil in OCaml!

%claude:
For example, after [[rc myscript.rc foo bar]] % is initialized,
the data structures look like this:
\begin{verbatim}
  runq ----> Thread
               code = bootstrap [1:Xrdcmds, 0]
               pc   = 1
               argv ----> List
                            words -> "myscript.rc" -> "foo" -> "bar" -> nil
                            next  = nil
               ret  = nil   (bottom of stack)
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
The real bootstrap code will then assign this word list to [[$*]]
and source [[rcmain]], which sets up [[$path]] and
runs the script.
% add ref to chapter real bootstrap?

%claude:
[<pushlist()>] pushes a new empty word list onto [[runq->argv]],
and [<pushword()>] adds a word to the current top list.
These two functions are the main interface for building
the argument stack and are used extensively by bytecodes
like [<Xmark()>] and [<Xword()>].

<<function [[pushlist]]>>=
/// main | Xmark ->  <>
void
pushlist(void)
{
    list *p = new(list);

    // add_list(p, runq->argv)
    p->next = runq->argv;
    p->words = nil;
    runq->argv = p;
}
@

% use runq, assume runq not nil! otherwise segfault


<<function [[pushword]]>>=
void
pushword(char *wd)
{
    if(runq->argv==nil)
        panic("pushword but no argv!", 0);
    runq->argv->words = newword(wd, runq->argv->words);
}
@
%ocaml: no need for panic, argv always at least empty list

% note that newword take the old value of the list so indeed
%  it adds wd in the list of words.


\section{Bytecode interpreter loop}

%claude:
The heart of [[rc]] is the infinite loop below.
It increments the program counter, then calls the function pointer
at the previous position. The increment-then-call-at-minus-one
pattern is a common idiom: the [[pc]] is advanced {\em before}
calling the bytecode function, so that if the bytecode needs to read
inline arguments (e.g., a string after [<Xword>]), it can
read them at [[runq->code[runq->pc]]] and advance [[pc]] itself.

<<[[main()]] interpreter loop>>=
for(;;){
    <<[[main()]] debug runq in interpreter loop>>

    runq->pc++;
