%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Input}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:input}
%spirit: %alt: so Lexing chapter cleaner

%claude: %toc: %trans: before yyparse, see routines used by yylex, called from yyparse.
Recall the main flow from Figure~\ref{fig:controlflow}:
[<main()>] $\rightarrow$ [<Xrdcmds()>] $\rightarrow$ [<yyparse()>]
$\rightarrow$ [<yylex()>].
%
Before describing the lexer, I will present the input routines
it relies on. These routines handle reading characters from
the current input source (terminal or script file), managing
the prompt, and providing the one-character lookahead
that the lexer needs.

\section{Overview}

%claude:
The call chain for reading input is shown below:
\begin{verbatim}
  yylex()
    |
    +---> nextc(); advance()   one-character lookahead (cached in 'future')
            |
            +---> getnext()      raw character read + prompt + escaped newlines
                    |
                    +---> rchr(runq->cmdfd)    buffered IO read
                            |
                            +---> read()       system call (terminal or file)
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
[<getnext()>] reads a raw character and handles
escaped newlines (for multi-line commands) and prompt display.
[<nextc()>] adds a one-character lookahead on top of [<getnext()>],
and [<advance()>] consumes that lookahead.


\section{Reading a character: [[getnext()]]}

%claude:
[<getnext()>] reads one character from the current thread's
input stream ([[runq->cmdfd]]).
%
Besides the actual read (via [<rchr()>], the buffered IO read function),
it handles three concerns:
returning a previously peeked character ([[peekc]]),
displaying the prompt before blocking on input, and
converting escaped newlines ([[\<newline>]]) into spaces to support multi-line commands.

<<function [[getnext]]>>=
/// yylex -> nextc -> <>
/*
 * read a character from the input stream
 */	
int
getnext(void)
{
    int c;
    <<[[getnext()]] other locals>>

    <<[[getnext()]] before read, peekc handling>>
    <<[[getnext()]] before read, return if already at EOF>>
    <<[[getnext()]] before read, prompt management>>

    c = rchr(runq->cmdfd);

    <<[[getnext()]] after read, handle backslash>>
    <<[[getnext()]] after read, prompt management>>
    <<[[getnext()]] after read, if EOF>>
    <<[[getnext()]] after read, if not EOF but verbose mode, print character read>>

    return c;
}
