\subsection{Multiple lines commands and escaped newlines}
\label{sec:escaping-newline}

%trans: more on "regular" newlines later.

%claude:
A backslash before a newline tells the shell that the
command continues on the next line. This lets you spread a long
command---a pipeline with many stages, or a command with many
arguments---over several lines for readability, without the shell
running it as soon as you press return.
%
[<getnext()>] detects this sequence and returns a space
instead of the newline, effectively joining the two lines.
If the backslash is followed by any other character,
it is not consumed: the backslash is returned normally,
and the next character is saved in [[peekc]] for the
next call.

