\section{Variables ([[<x>=...]])}
%alt: definitions

%claude:
Variable assignment in [[rc]] is written [[x=value]].
The interesting aspect is that an assignment can be followed
by a command: [[x=value cmd]] makes the assignment local
to that command only. When [[cmd]] is empty, the assignment is global.
%
The assignment appears {\em before} the command, following
the Bourne shell convention (which was itself motivated by
programs like [[make]] that accept [[x=y]] on the command line).%
\footnote{The two are not the same: [[x=y mk]] is a shell assignment,
so [[rc]] sets [[x]] in the environment that [[mk]] inherits, whereas
[[mk x=y]] passes [[x=y]] as an argument that [[mk]] itself parses as
an [[mkfile]] variable assignment. Both end up defining [[x]] for the
build---since [[mk]] also imports the environment---but by different
paths.}


<<cmd rule other cases>>=
|   assign cmd                    %prec BANG
      {$$=mung3($1, $1->child[0], $1->child[1], $2);}
