%claude:
A [[comword]] is the smallest standalone argument the grammar
recognizes. Besides a bare [[WORD]], it covers variable expansion
([[$x]]), the element count [[$#x]] ([[COUNT]]), and subscripting
[[$x(n)]] ([[SUB]]). The last relies on a small lexer trick: a [[(]]
normally begins a list, but when it comes right after a word the lexer
(seeing its [[lastword]] flag set) returns the distinct [[SUB]] token
instead and consumes the [[(]], so [[$x(1 2)]] is parsed as a
subscript rather than as [[$x]] next to a separate list.

<<comword rule other cases>>=
|   '$' word        {$$=tree1('$', $2);}
|   COUNT word      {$$=tree1(COUNT, $2);}
|   '$' word SUB words ')'  {$$=tree2(SUB, $2, $4);}
@
%$

