%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Environment}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:environment}

%claude:
Under \plan
%, the environment is not passed via the [[envp]]
%parameter of [[main()]] as in \unix. Instead,
each environment
variable is stored as a file under [[/env/]]: the variable
[[$path]] is stored in [[/env/path]].
%
This is a more elegant
design than \unix because child processes automatically inherit the
environment through the {\em namespace} (see the \book{Kernel}),
and changes are visible to all processes sharing the same namespace.
%
In \unix the environment is part of the process {\em image}: [[exec]]
copies the [[environ]] array (alongside [[argv]]) into the new process,
so a child gets its own copy and can never change its parent's
environment. Under \plan, because [[/env]] is just shared state in the
namespace, a child {\em can} modify variables that its parent and
siblings will then see---more flexibility. A process that instead wants
a private environment forks with [[rfork(RFENVG)]], which gives it its
own copy of [[/env]].

%claude:
[[rc]] must synchronize its internal variable table
with these files in both directions: [<Updenv()>] writes
changed variables to [[/env/]], and [<Vinit()>] reads
variables from [[/env/]] at startup.

\section{Writing variables to [[/env/]]: [[Updenv()]]}

%claude:
[<Updenv()>] iterates over all global and local variables
and writes any that have changed (with [[v->changed == true]])
to the [[/env/]] filesystem. The [[changed]] flag
avoids redundant writes.

<<function [[Updenv]]>>=
/// Xsimple | Execute -> <>
void
Updenv(void)
{
    var *v, **h;

    for(h = gvar;h!=&gvar[NVAR];h++)
        for(v=*h;v;v = v->next)
            addenv(v);
    if(runq)
        updenvlocal(runq->local);
}
@

<<function [[updenvlocal]]>>=
void
updenvlocal(var *v)
{
    if(v){
        updenvlocal(v->next);
        addenv(v);
    }
}
@


<<enum [[MiscPlan9]]>>=
enum {
    Maxenvname = 256,	/* undocumented limit */
};
@

<<[[Var]] other fields>>=
bool	changed;
@

<<function [[addenv]](plan9.c)>>=
void
addenv(var *v)
{
    char envname[Maxenvname];
    word *w;
    fdt f;
    io *fd;

    if(v->changed){
        v->changed = false;
        snprint(envname, sizeof envname, "/env/%s", v->name);
        f = Creat(envname);
        if(f<0)
            pfmt(err, "rc: can't open %s: %r\n", envname);
        else{
            for(w = v->val;w;w = w->next)
                write(f, w->word, strlen(w->word)+1L);
            close(f);
        }
    }
    <<[[addenv()]] if [[fnchanged]]>>
}
@

<<[[addenv()]] if [[fnchanged]]>>=
if(v->fnchanged){
    v->fnchanged = false;
    snprint(envname, sizeof envname, "/env/fn#%s", v->name);
    f = Creat(envname);
    if(f<0)
        pfmt(err, "rc: can't open %s: %r\n", envname);
    else{
        if(v->fn){
            fd = openfd(f);
            pfmt(fd, "fn %q %s\n", v->name, v->fn[v->pc-1].s);
            closeio(fd);
        }
        close(f);
    }
}
@

\section{Reading variables from [[/env/]]: [[Vinit()]]}

%claude:
[<Vinit()>] reads the [[/env/]] directory at startup and
populates the global variable table.
Each environment file contains the variable's words
separated by null bytes. [<Vinit()>] reads the file,
splits on nulls, and calls [<setvar()>] for each variable.
It then resets the [[changed]] flag so that [<Updenv()>]
does not write them back immediately.
%plan9-is-better:
The null byte separator is the only safe choice: unlike
spaces or newlines, null bytes cannot appear in filenames
or variable values, so the encoding is unambiguous.
This is the same insight behind \unix tools like
[[find -print0]] and [[xargs -0]].

<<function [[Vinit]]>>=
/// main -> <>
void
Vinit(void)
{
    int dir, f, len, i, n, nent;
    char *buf, *s;
    char envname[Maxenvname];
    word *val;
    Dir *ent;

    dir = open("/env", OREAD);
    if(dir<0){
        pfmt(err, "rc: can't open /env: %r\n");
        return;
    }
    ent = nil;
    for(;;){
        nent = dirread(dir, &ent);
        if(nent <= 0)
            break;
        for(i = 0; i<nent; i++){
            len = ent[i].length;
            if(len && strncmp(ent[i].name, "fn#", 3)!=0){
                snprint(envname, sizeof envname, "/env/%s", ent[i].name);
                if((f = open(envname, 0))>=0){
                    buf = emalloc(len+1);
                    n = readn(f, buf, len);
                    if (n <= 0)
                        buf[0] = '\0';
                    else
                        buf[n] = '\0';
                    val = 0;
                    /* Charitably add a 0 at the end if need be */
                    if(buf[len-1])
                        buf[len++]='\0';
                    s = buf+len-1;
                    for(;;){
                        while(s!=buf && s[-1]!='\0') --s;
                        val = newword(s, val);
                        if(s==buf)
                            break;
                        --s;
                    }
                    setvar(ent[i].name, val);
                    vlook(ent[i].name)->changed = false;
                    close(f);
                    efree(buf);
                }
            }
        }
        free(ent);
    }
    close(dir);
}
@

<<global [[envdir]]>>=
fdt envdir;
@

\section{Special variables}
\label{sec:special-variables}
%alt: in Env chapter? in Init chapter? in Var codegen section?

%claude: %trans:
The environment is also where [[rc]]'s {\em special variables} live:
ordinary variables by name, but ones the shell itself consults to decide
how it behaves. Here are a few of the most important, many of them given
their defaults in [[rcmain]] (see Section~\ref{sec:rcmain}):

%claude:
\begin{itemize}

\item [[$prompt]] --- the two prompt strings (main and continuation),
  printed by the input loop (Section~\ref{sec:display-prompt}).

\item [[$status]] --- the exit status of the last command, as a
  string ([[rc]]'s answer to the Bourne shell's [[$?]]), set through
  [<setstatus()>]/[<getstatus()>].
% $status far clearer than $0
% and under plan9 string, not int so clearer

\item [[$home]] --- the user's home directory, used by [[cd]] with no
  argument and to locate [[$home/lib/profile]]. Unlike the \unix shells,
  [[rc]] offers no \verb+~+ shortcut for it; you spell out [[$home]].

\item [[$path]] --- the list of directories searched for external
  commands by [<searchpath()>].

\item [[$cdpath]] --- the list of directories [[cd]] searches when given
  a relative directory name, the [[cd]] analogue of [[$path]]; [[cd]]
  echoes the directory it lands in when it was reached through a
  [[$cdpath]] entry rather than the current directory.

\item [[$*]] --- the argument list of the script or function;
  [[$1]], [[$2]], \ldots index into it (via [[Xdol()]]).

% * (TODO aspectize vlook("*") code)

\item [[$ifs]] --- the field separators used to split the output of a
  backquote substitution \verb+`{...}+ into words.
\end{itemize}

%claude: %plan9-is-cleaner:
One small but telling difference: [[rc]] spells these [[$home]],
[[$path]], [[$prompt]], where the \unix shells shout [[HOME]], [[PATH]],
[[PS1]]. The uppercase convention exists in [[sh]] only to keep exported
environment variables from colliding with the lowercase names a script
picks for its own scratch variables. [[rc]] has no second class of names
to stay clear of---every variable already lives in the one [[/env]]
namespace---so it can use the quieter lowercase spellings.



\section{[[% finit]]}
\label{sec:builtin-finit}
%alt: Functions in the environment
%alt: move in Environment chapter, in advanced builtins

%claude:
The [[finit]] builtin re-reads function definitions
from the [[/env]] filesystem.
%
This is Plan~9-specific:
when another process (e.g., a parent shell) defines a
function, it appears as a file \verb+/env/fn#name+.
%
[[finit]] scans [[/env]] for these \verb+fn#+ files
and executes them to import the function definitions
into the current shell.
%
It uses a small hand-crafted
bytecode loop ([[rdfns]]) similar to the bootstrap
code, with [[Xrdfn]] reading one function file per
iteration.

<<global [[rdfns]]>>=
union Code rdfns[4];
@

<<function [[execfinit]]>>=
/// "finit" builtin -> <>
void
execfinit(void)
{
